stent manner, we obtain a simple theory for the self-energy of an ion that is continuous across the interface. Along with nonelectrostatic contributions, our theory enables a unified description of ions on both sides of the interface. Using intrinsic parameters of the ions, we predict the specific ion effect on the interfacial affinity of halogen anions at the water-air interface, and the strong adsorption of hydrophobic ions at the water-oil interface, in agreement with experiments and atomistic simulations. Â© 2014 American Physical Society.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84898080685" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84898080685&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84898080685%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60031581" id="60031581"><affilname>California Institute of Technology</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="55881085400" seq="1"><ce:initials>R.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Wang R.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Wang</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Rui</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>R.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Wang R.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Wang</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Rui</ce:given-name></preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/55881085400</author-url><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60031581" id="60031581"/></author><author auid="7410040846" seq="2"><ce:initials>Z.-G.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Wang Z.-G.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Wang</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Zhen-Gang</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>Z.G.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Wang Z.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Wang</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Zhen Gang</ce:given-name></preferred-name><author-